<font color="#FF0000">FRAGGINGS AND REFUSALS</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jun  2  1:18:24 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To all,<br><br>
     I have read many stories on fraggings in Vietnam, and some appear to be just stories, others seem true.  As a student of history, I think that fragging has become some ultimate folklore, interesting but overplayed.  I can't imagine it going on as frequent as the history books on Vietnam portray it.  My father recounts stories that were passed around, but had no such incidences in his unit.  Tom is right.  All fraggings are murder, and many must be a cover up, when the truth about something is discovered.  In that regard, then fraggings are not exceptional, but the same as when some criminal kills to protect a secret.<br><br>
Here is my question for discussion.  I've heard a lot about &quot;combat refusals&quot;, men refusing to be a order that they perceived to be stupid.  It seems to have happened to all branches during the latter stages of the war (1969-1972).  I believe CBS recorded a company of men rufusing to walk a trail in a documentary featuring C Company 2/7 1st CAV Division.  Also saw a news report where a group of men refused to advance up a hill.  I've read of mass refusals, when groups of men refused an order and never were court martialed (1st Cav had 35 incidents of refusal in 1969 alone).  I've read that some refusals amounted to not putting out night ambushes (Tim O'Brien talks about this in his book-IF I DIE IN A COMBAT ZONE) or not completing patrols (giving wrong map coordinates).  <br><br>
Here is my question-Do any of the Vets here remember someone refusing a combat order?  If so, what became of the person or persons?  My father has told me a few accounts that he heard of and I would like to hear what you gentlemen remember as well.         
<p><code>-- E-Mail on request  (Joe DeLeva) </code><p>


